White bars on back seemed narrow and did not continue to nape so black patch present below nape. Hind crown black was thick and facial white markings were narrow and white nasal tufts were extensive. Hybrid or Ladder-backed traits were not apparent to me.

Observation Details: In the eastern end of the main park, northeast of the bathrooms, in a circular grove of Black Walnut trees, I heard an intermittent, soft tapping. I moved slowly around the trees and saw, first one, then three Nutall's Woodpeckers. For a moment, all three were on the trunk of a single tree, then two remained together, while an adult female flew to an adjacent tree. All were mainly black and white with black back and wings, heavily spotted and barred with white. The barring did not extend all the way up the back. One bird had a distinct area of red at the nape to the rear crown of the head, and remained with a second bird that had a red area farther forward on the crown. The first bird actively fed the younger bird. On a second tree, another adult was all black and white, in similar pattern, with no evidence of any red coloring.

Observation Details: This bird attracted my attention by giving a straight whinny rattle (not descending as in Ladder-backed). It flew to another location where I could see a black back interrupted by narrow white bars, and there was an unbarred solid black area at the upper back below the neck which was connected to a solid black hind neck. Those are my supporting details, conversely I could not examine the tail for barring vs spots, nor did I see the side of the face - so I am unable to call it a possible hybrid. The nearby San Felipe Creek area is a contact zone for the two species mentioned here.

Observation Details: Looks for the most part to be a pure male. I think the first one fitting into the Nuttall's box for the Coachella Valley in Riverside County.

Photographed. This bird looks good for a female Nuttall's Woodpecker. The white lines on the face are thin, and the outer tail feathers match Nuttall's as well. Additionally, the bird has a white spot at the base of the bill which is much more dull on Ladder-backed Woodpeckers.  The bird also called, and I've listened to recordings and it sounded very good for a Nuttall's Woodpecker.

Observation Details: In the eastern end of the main park, northeast of the bathrooms, in a circular grove of Black Walnut trees, I heard an intermittent, soft tapping. I moved slowly around the trees and saw, first one, then three Nutall's Woodpeckers. For a moment, all three were on the trunk of a single tree, then two remained together, while an adult female flew to an adjacent tree. All were mainly black and white with black back and wings, heavily spotted and barred with white. The barring did not extend all the way up the back. One bird had a distinct area of red at the nape to the rear crown of the head, and remained with a second bird that had a red area farther forward on the crown. The first bird actively fed the younger bird. On a second tree, another adult was all black and white, in similar pattern, with no evidence of any red coloring.

Observation Details: Two adults repeatedly coming with food to nest cavity in thin dead redwood in little grove just east of caretaker’s house. The volume of the begging sounds indicated at least two nestlings, but cavity hole only allowed the viewing of one clearly at a time. One photo seems to possibly show a second nestling head. Young clearly had extensive red crown. Cavity appeared to be only about 3-4 feet above the ground.

Couple bringing food to nest hole in sycamore.

Both male and female adults observed bringing insects and feeding young.   At least two nestlings were being fed; a second lacked the red forehead patch as shown by the young being fed in the photo.  Feedings took place every ~5 minutes or so, and during this observation period consisted mainly of Earwigs (insect order Dermaptera).  Almost continuously between feedings the young birds made a quiet squeaky chattering "pip".  Both young appear to be close to fledging.  About 30 cm higher up and on opposite side of broken-out trunk a pair of House Wrens had nested in another cavity and were bringing insects at the same time.

Observation Details: In the eastern end of the main park, northeast of the bathrooms, in a circular grove of Black Walnut trees, I heard an intermittent, soft tapping. I moved slowly around the trees and saw, first one, then three Nutall's Woodpeckers. For a moment, all three were on the trunk of a single tree, then two remained together, while an adult female flew to an adjacent tree. All were mainly black and white with black back and wings, heavily spotted and barred with white. The barring did not extend all the way up the back. One bird had a distinct area of red at the nape to the rear crown of the head, and remained with a second bird that had a red area farther forward on the crown. The first bird actively fed the younger bird. On a second tree, another adult was all black and white, in similar pattern, with no evidence of any red coloring.

Observation Details: Male feeding nestling at nest cavity in large, dead branch of live oak near barbecue pit. The food item looked like an earwig. I discovered this nest a week or two ago. Today there seemed to be just one nestling, and it seemed close to fledging, as it spent most of its time peering out of the nest hole, sometimes sticking its head and neck all the way out. It also looked large and gave an adult-like call at one point, in addition to its begging calls. I'm guessing its siblings have already fledged and are being accompanied by the adult female. This may be the same pair I saw starting to excavate a nest cavity in a nearby tree earlier in May.

Observation Details: 1 adult female.   1 adult male with a probable plumage variation to its face, having a heavily demarcated black throat, in addition to the exposure of presumably a sticky sap/nectar on its face, creating a buffy/brown patina to its possibly, once white, malar, bleeding down past its black throat onto its upper breast. This particular sap/nectar staining is starting to be apparent on the female Nuttall’s face and throat as well, although is more brown in appearance vs black, like on the male Nuttall’s.   Both loosely associating with the Yellow-bellied Sapsucker.

Observation Details: 1 adult female.   1 adult male with a plumage variation of having an overall dark face - suggested either due to feather wear, or environmental factors such as exposure to mucky cavities -an adult male Nuttall’s Woodpecker (NUWO), with a red crown, solid black on its upper back; horizontal white stripes on its back and white spots on its wing; whitish underbelly with black spots. However, it has an off-white/buffy nasal tuft; the black spots seems to be all over on its underside vs being limited to along its sides like a NUWO; its malar, that’s typically white is dingy, almost black, including its throat.  Thank you, Tom W, for your review of this interesting guy!! :))
